{"atom_id":"ig34_p0392_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":392,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 3","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Each of the paths for the trial illustrated in the following diagram goes through one branch point at randomization, and then through another branch point when response is evaluated. This results in 4 arms, corresponding to the number of possible paths through the trial, and also to the number of blocks at the right end of the diagram. The fact that there are only 2 kinds of block at the right end (Open DRUG X and Rescue) does not affect the fact that there are 4 paths and thus 4 arms.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0392_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":392,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 3","atom_type":"FIGURE","verbatim":"[FIGURE: Example Trial 3, Multiple Branches Study Schema — diagram showing Screen block branching at Randomization to Drug A and Drug B; Drug A branches to Open A and Rescue; Drug B branches to Open A and Rescue; Response Evaluation label at second branch]","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":"pdf_p0392+middle","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0392_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":392,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 3","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The next diagram for this trial is the prospective view. It shows the epochs of the trial and how the initial group of subjects is split into 2 treatment groups for the double-blind treatment epoch, and how each of those initial treatment groups is split in 2 at the response evaluation, resulting in the 4 arms of this trial The names of the arms have been chosen to represent the outcomes of the successive branches that, together, assign subjects to arms. These compound names were chosen to facilitate description of subjects who may drop out of the trial after the first branch and before the second branch. Example 7 in Section 5.2, Demographics, illustrates DM and Subject Elements (SE) data for such subjects.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["§5.2"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0392_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":392,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 3","atom_type":"FIGURE","verbatim":"[FIGURE: Example Trial 3, Multiple Branches Prospective View — diagram showing Screening Epoch, Double Blind Treatment Epoch (Drug A and Drug B rows), Open Treatment Epoch (Open A and Rescue for each); arms labeled A-Open, A-Rescue, B-Open, B-Rescue; Randomization and Response Evaluation arrows at bottom]","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":"pdf_p0392+bottom","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
