{"atom_id":"ig34_p0394_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":394,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 4","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The following diagram uses a new symbol, a large curved arrow representing the fact that the chemotherapy treatment (A or B) and the rest period that follows it are to be repeated. In this trial, the chemotherapy cycles are to be repeated until disease progression. Although some chemotherapy trials specify a maximum number of cycles, protocols that allow an indefinite number of repeats are not uncommon.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0394_a019","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":394,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 4","atom_type":"FIGURE","verbatim":"[FIGURE: Example Trial 4, Cyclical Chemotherapy Study Schema — diagram showing Screen block branching at Randomization to Drug A and Drug B arms; each arm has Drug→Rest with curved repeat arrow, then Follow; label 'Repeat until disease progression']","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":"pdf_p0394+bottom","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0394_a020","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":394,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 4","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The next diagram shows the prospective view of this trial. Note that, in spite of the repeating element structure, this is, at its core, a 2-arm parallel study, and thus has 2 arms. In SDTMIG 3.1.1, there was an implicit assumption that each element must be in a separate epoch, and trials with cyclical chemotherapy were difficult to handle. The introduction of the concept of study cells and the dropping of the assumption that elements and epochs have a one-to-one relationship resolved these difficulties. This trial is best treated as having just 3 epochs, since the main objectives of the trial involve comparisons between the 2 treatments and do not require data to be considered cycle by cycle.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0395_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":395,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§7.2.1 Trial Arms (TA) – Example 4","atom_type":"FIGURE","verbatim":"[FIGURE: Example Trial 4, Cyclical Chemotherapy Prospective View — diagram showing Screening Epoch, Treatment Epoch (Drug A/Rest/Repeat until disease progression and Drug B/Rest/Repeat until disease progression rows), Follow-up Epoch; arms Drug A and Drug B; Randomization arrow]","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":"pdf_p0395+top","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.5","ts":"2026-04-29T00:00:00Z"}}
